You’re right that metadata can be very valuable in aggregate over time. That’s why people sometimes compare large datasets to resources like oil or gold — the value isn’t in a single data point, but in patterns that emerge when many signals are combined.

A few reasons metadata is useful:

1. Pattern detection

Things like timestamps, location pings, device types, and usage logs help systems understand:
	•	traffic flows
	•	network performance
	•	product usage patterns
	•	fraud or security anomalies

When aggregated across millions of users, that can reveal trends that aren’t visible from individual records.

2. Optimization

Companies and researchers often use aggregated metadata to improve systems, for example:
	•	routing and mapping services
	•	load balancing in networks
	•	product design decisions
	•	scientific modeling

3. Economic value

Large-scale datasets can become valuable because they enable:
	•	better recommendations
	•	predictive analytics
	•	operational efficiency

That’s why you sometimes hear the phrase “data is the new oil.”

4. Safeguards and constraints

At the same time, there are usually privacy controls and regulations around how data and metadata can be collected and used, especially when it could identify individuals. Different jurisdictions have different laws and policies aimed at limiting misuse.

⸻

So the intuition that aggregated metadata can have real economic and analytical value is accurate. But the practical reality is that it’s usually handled within technical, legal, and organizational frameworks rather than being a free-for-all resource.